ment, Mourning, and the Tradition of Elegy in Early Scholem -- tSection Six: Mourning, Ruin and Lament -- tParadoxes of Lament: Benjamin and Hamlet -- tThe Tradition in Ruins: Walter Benjamin and Gershom Scholem on Language and Lament -- tSection Seven: Translations of Gershom Scholem's Texts on Lament -- tTranslators' Introduction -- tOn Lament and Lamentation -- tJob's Lament -- tTranslation of Job Chapter 3: Job's Lament -- tEzekiel Chapter 19: A Lamentation for Israel's Last Princes -- tTranslation of Ezekiel Chapter 19: A Lamentation for Israel's Last Princes -- tA Medieval Lamentation -- tTranslation of Sha'ali Serufa: A Medieval Lamentation -- tScholem's postscript in the manuscript version -- tNotes on Contributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aLament, mourning, and the transmissibility of a tradition in the aftermath of destruction are prominent themes in Jewish thought. The corpus of lament literature, building upon and transforming the biblical Book of Lamentations, provides a unique lens for thinking about the relationships between destruction and renewal, mourning and remembrance, loss and redemption, expression and the inexpressible. This anthology features four texts by Gershom Scholem on lament, translated here for the first time into English. The volume also includes original essays by leading scholars, which interpret Scholem's texts and situate them in relation to other Weimar-era Jewish thinkers, including Walter Benjamin, Franz Rosenzweig, Franz Kafka, and Paul Celan, who drew on the textual traditions of lament to respond to the destruction and upheavals of the early twentieth century. Also included are studies on the textual tradition of lament in Judaism, from biblical, rabbinic, and medieval lamentations to contemporary Yemenite women's laments. This collection, unified by its strong thematic focus on lament, shows the fruitfulness of studying contemporary and modern texts alongside the traditional textual sources that informed them.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aJewish mourning customsxPhilosophy. 0aJewish philosophy. 0aLaments in the Bible. 0aLamentsxPhilosophy. 4aJüdisches Denken. 4aKlage. 4aScholem, Gershom. 4aTrauer. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aGershom Scholem.  aJewish Thought.  aLament.  aMourning.1 aBarouch, Lina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielik-Robson, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComay, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerber, Ilit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerber, Ilit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalbertal, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamacher, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan-Rokem, Galit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipszyc, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadar, Vered, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSauter, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScholem, Gershom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchonfeld, Eli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwebel, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwebel, Paula, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabul